                'id' => 1,
                'title' => 'How to Choose a Granite Headstone in Waco',
                'slug' => 'how-to-choose-granite-headstone-waco',
                'body' => '<h2>How to Choose a Granite Headstone in Waco</h2><p>Choosing a headstone for a loved one is one of the most personal decisions a family can make. It is a lasting tribute — something that will stand for generations and tell the story of a life well lived. If you are beginning this process for the first time, it can feel overwhelming. There are styles to consider, granite colors to choose from, personalization options to explore, and a budget to keep in mind.</p><p>At Dietz Memorial, we have been guiding Central Texas families through this process since 1903. Here is everything you need to know before you visit our Waco showroom.</p><h3>Step 1 — Choose the Right Style</h3><p>The first decision is the overall style of the headstone. There are four main options:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Upright Headstones </strong> — The most traditional and recognizable style. Stands vertically above the ground and offers the most surface area for personalization, engraving, and artwork. A classic choice for most families.</p></li><li><p><strong>Flat Markers </strong>— Lies flat on the ground, flush with the grass. Many cemeteries require this style, especially in newer sections. Simple and clean in appearance.</p></li><li><p><strong>Bevel Markers </strong>— Slightly raised at the back and angled toward the front, making it easy to read. A popular middle ground between upright and flat styles.</p></li><li><p><strong>Slant Markers </strong>— Has a gently angled face that is easy to read from a standing position. Offers a traditional look with a lower profile than a full upright headstone.</p></li></ul><p>Before choosing a style, always check with your cemetery. Many have specific rules about what types of markers are permitted in each section.</p><h3>Step 2 — Pick the Right Granite Color</h3><p>Granite is a natural stone and comes in a wide range of colors. Each color has unique characteristics that affect how engravings and artwork appear on the surface.</p><ul><li><p><strong>Black granite</strong> — The most popular choice. Shows white engravings with exceptional contrast and sharpness. Ideal for portraits and detailed artwork.</p></li><li><p><strong>Gray granite</strong> — A classic, timeless look. Works well for traditional engraving styles.</p></li><li><p><strong>Pink and red granite</strong> — Warm, distinctive tones that stand out beautifully in outdoor settings.</p></li><li><p><strong>Mahogany granite</strong> — A deep reddish-brown stone with natural variation that gives each memorial a unique character.</p></li><li><p><strong>Blue pearl granite</strong> — An imported stone with a distinctive shimmering blue-gray tone. Often chosen for its striking appearance.</p></li></ul><p>We recommend visiting our Waco showroom to see real granite samples in person. Colors look very different on a screen compared to how they appear in natural light.</p><h3>Step 3 — Think About Personalization</h3><p>A headstone is far more than a name and two dates. Modern granite memorials can be deeply personalized to reflect the unique life of your loved one.</p><ul><li><p><strong>Laser-etched portraits</strong> — A photograph of your loved one can be permanently etched into the granite surface with remarkable detail and clarity.</p></li><li><p><strong>Military insignia and emblems </strong>— Branch of service, rank, and unit insignia can be engraved with precision.</p></li><li><p><strong>Religious symbols</strong> — Crosses, Stars of David, doves, and other symbols of faith.</p></li><li><p><strong>Custom artwork </strong>— Landscapes, hobbies, flowers, animals, or any design that reflects who your loved one was.</p></li><li><p><strong>Scripture and poetry </strong>— A meaningful verse, quote, or poem that captures the spirit of their life.</p></li><li><p><strong>Decorative borders and motifs</strong> — Frame the memorial with elegant design elements that complement the overall look.</p></li></ul><h3>Step 4 — Set a Realistic Budget</h3><p>Headstone prices vary depending on several factors — the size of the stone, the style, the type of granite, and the amount of personalization. Larger upright monuments with detailed artwork cost more than simple flat markers with basic engraving.</p><p>At Dietz Memorial, we believe every family deserves a quality memorial regardless of budget. We will never pressure you to spend more than is comfortable, and we will always show you honest options at every price point. We encourage you to shop with us before paying too much elsewhere.</p><h3>Step 5 — Work With a Trusted Local Memorial Company</h3><p>Choosing a local memorial company means working with people who understand your community, know the cemeteries in your area, and will be there to stand behind their work. Dietz Memorial has served Central Texas families from Waco since 1903. We handle everything from design to delivery and installation.</p><h3>Ready to Get Started?</h3><p>Visit our Waco showroom at 500 LaSalle Ave, Waco, TX. Our team is here Monday through Friday to guide you with compassion, patience, and expertise. There is no pressure and no rush — just honest help when you need it most.</p><p>Call us at 254-756-5315 or visit our website to learn more about our services and gallery of completed memorials.</p>',
