                'title' => 'Bronze vs Granite Markers — Which Is Right for You',
                'slug' => 'bronze-vs-granite-markers',
                'body' => '<h2>Bronze vs Granite Markers — Which Is Right for You</h2><p>When the time comes to choose a memorial for a loved one, one of the first decisions families face is the choice of material. Two options stand above the rest — bronze and granite. Both have been used for generations, both are beautiful and durable, and both can be deeply personalized. But they are different in important ways, and the right choice depends on your cemetery, your budget, and your vision for the memorial.</p><p>At Dietz Memorial, we work with both materials every day and are happy to help you find the right fit. Here is an honest comparison to help you get started.</p><h3>Granite Markers</h3><p>Granite is a natural stone that has been the foundation of memorial design for centuries. It is one of the hardest and most weather-resistant materials on earth, which makes it ideal for outdoor memorials that need to last for generations.</p><h3>Advantages of Granite</h3><ul><li><p><strong>Wide range of colors </strong>— Granite comes in gray, black, pink, red, mahogany, blue pearl, and more. Each color has its own character and works differently with engraving.</p></li><li><p><strong>Highly customizable </strong> — Granite can be engraved with portraits, custom artwork, scripture, poems, military insignia, and detailed designs.</p></li><li><p><strong>Versatile styles</strong> — Works for upright headstones, flat markers, bevel markers, and slant markers.</p></li><li><p><strong>Generally more affordable</strong> — Granite tends to cost less than bronze for comparable sizes.</p></li><li><p><strong>Very low maintenance </strong>— Granite requires little to no ongoing care.</p></li></ul><h3>Disadvantages of Granite</h3><ul><li><p><strong>Heavier than bronze</strong> — This can affect shipping and installation.</p></li><li><p><strong>Cemetery restrictions</strong> — Some cemeteries only allow flat markers, which limits upright granite options.</p></li></ul><h3>Bronze Markers</h3><p>Bronze markers are flat plaques, typically mounted on a granite base. They carry a classic, dignified appearance and have long been associated with veteran memorials and memorial parks across the country.</p><h3>Advantages of Bronze</h3><ul><li><p><strong>Timeless appearance</strong> — Bronze has a distinguished, traditional look that never goes out of style.</p></li><li><p><strong>Universally accepted </strong>— Bronze flat markers are accepted in virtually every cemetery in the country.</p></li><li><p><strong>Clear, legible text </strong>— The raised lettering and designs on bronze markers are easy to read for decades.</p></li><li><p><strong>Official veteran marker material </strong>— Bronze is the standard material used for government-furnished veteran grave markers.</p></li><li><p><strong>Beautiful patina over time</strong> — Bronze develops a natural aged finish that many families find meaningful.</p></li></ul><h3>Disadvantages of Bronze</h3><ul><li><p><strong>Higher cost </strong>— Bronze markers are typically more expensive than comparable granite options.</p></li><li><p><strong>Requires occasional cleaning</strong> — Bronze can oxidize and may need periodic cleaning to maintain its appearance.</p></li><li><p><strong>Limited color variety</strong> — Bronze comes in a standard finish, unlike the wide color range of granite.</p></li></ul><h3>Which Should You Choose?</h3><p>If your cemetery requires a flat marker and you want a classic, dignified look — bronze is an excellent choice, especially for veterans or traditional memorial parks.</p><p>If you want more flexibility in style, more color options, a wider range of personalization, or a more affordable option — granite is the way to go.</p><p>Many families also choose a combination — a granite base with a bronze plaque on top — which gives you the best of both materials.</p><h3>Come See Both in Person</h3><p>The best way to decide is to see real samples with your own eyes. Visit our showroom in Waco at 500 LaSalle Ave or our New Braunfels location and our team will walk you through every option with no pressure and no rush. Call us at 254-756-5315 and we will be happy to help.</p>',
                'excerpt' => 'Not sure whether to choose a bronze or granite memorial marker? We break down the differences so you can make the best choice for your loved one.',
